<dl id="n42046e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n42" href="#n42046e">N42 (VI.B.31)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n42all.htm#n42046e"> 46(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> brain of Franks / hands of Chinese / tongue of Arabs <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n42046e"><li>FW 127.29 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n42046e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n42046e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n42046e">MS BL 47475-53</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:245 <a name="fad6" href="../../FF/fdra/fda.htm#fad6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fa/fad6.htm#n42046e">Draft: I.6&sect;1.6</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Damiri has a saying, &ldquo;Wisdom hath alighted on three things, <mark>the brain of the Franks, the hands of the Chinese, and the tongue of the Arabs</mark>,&rdquo; and the last is not the least true. <small> Stanley Lane-Poole, <a name="SLPS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SLPS"><cite title="source">The Speeches and Table-Talk of the Prophet Mohammad</cite></a> (1882) xvii</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
